"Vicente-Serrano S.M., Beguería S., López-Moreno J.I.","A multiscalar drought index sensitive to global warming: The standardized precipitation evapotranspiration index",2010,"Journal of Climate","23","7",,"1696","1718",,,10.1175/2009JCLI2909.1,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77953696347&partnerID=40&md5=41edbc751b5c1ecd87f5c518850803f5","Instituto Pirenaico de Ecología, Zaragoza, Spain; Estación Experimental de Aula Dei, Zaragoza, Spain","Vicente-Serrano, S.M., Instituto Pirenaico de Ecología, Zaragoza, Spain; Beguería, S., Estación Experimental de Aula Dei, Zaragoza, Spain; López-Moreno, J.I., Instituto Pirenaico de Ecología, Zaragoza, Spain","The authors propose a new climatic drought index: the standardized precipitation evapotranspiration index (SPEI). The SPEI is based on precipitation and temperature data, and it has the advantage of combining multiscalar character with the capacity to include the effects of temperature variability on drought assessment. The procedure to calculate the index is detailed and involves a climatic water balance, the accumulation of deficit/surplus at different time scales, and adjustment to a log-logistic probability distribution. Mathematically, the SPEI is similar to the standardized precipitation index (SPI), but it includes the role of temperature. Because the SPEI is based on a water balance, it can be compared to the self-calibrated Palmer drought severity index (sc-PDSI). Time series of the three indices were compared for a set of observatories with different climate characteristics, located in different parts of the world. Under global warming conditions, only the sc-PDSI and SPEI identified an increase in drought severity associated with higher water demand as a result of evapotranspiration. Relative to the sc-PDSI, the SPEI has the advantage of being multiscalar, which is crucial for drought analysis and monitoring. © 2010 American Meteorological Society.",,"Climate characteristics; Climatic water balance; Different time scale; Drought analysis; Drought indices; Drought severity; Effects of temperature; Log-logistic; Palmer drought severity indices; Standardized precipitation index; Temperature data; Water balance; Water demand; Evapotranspiration; Global warming; Probability distributions; Temperature; Time series; Water supply; Drought; air temperature; drought; evapotranspiration; global warming; precipitation (climatology); precipitation assessment; water budget",,,,,,"Abramopoulos, F., Rosenzweig, C., Choudhury, B., Improved ground hydrology calculations for global climate models (GCMs): Soil water movement and evapotranspiration (1988) J. Climate, 1, pp. 921-941; Abramowitz, M., Stegun, I.A., (1965) Handbook of Mathematical Functions, with Formulas, Graphs, and Mathematical Tables, p. 1046. , Dover Publications; Ahmad, M.I., Sinclair, C.D., Werritty, A., Log-logistic flood frequency analysis (1988) J. Hydrol., 98, pp. 205-224; Akinremi, O.O., McGinn, S.M., Barr, A.G., Evaluation of the Palmer drought index on the Canadian prairies (1996) J. Climate, 9, pp. 897-905; Allen, R.G., Pereira, L.S., Raes, D., Smith, M., (1998) Crop evapotranspiration: Guidelines for computing crop water requirements, p. 300. , FAO Irrigation and Drainage Paper 56; Alley, W.M., The Palmer drought severity index: Limitations and applications (1984) J. Appl. Meteor., 23, pp. 1100-1109; Beniston, M., Future extreme events in European climate: An exploration of regional climate model projections (2007) Climatic Change, 81 (SUPPL. 1), pp. 71-95; Burton, I., Kates, R.W., White, G.F., (1978) The Environment as Hazard, p. 240. , Oxford University Press; Chang, T.J., Cleopa, X.A., A proposed method for drought monitoring (1991) Water Resour. Bull., 27, pp. 275-281; Changnon, S.A., Easterling, W.E., Measuring drought impacts: The Illinois case (1989) Water Resour. Bull., 25, pp. 27-42; Droogers, P., Allen, R.G., Estimating reference evapotranspiration under inaccurate data conditions (2002)